A medium-power earthquake with a magnitude of 5.1 struck the Aleutian Islands off the coast of Alaska. This comes only two days after the archipelago was hit by a 6.6-magnitude jolt, which was only 5 miles from land, according to the US Geological Survey. According to the USGS, the quake was at a depth of 4,929 feet. The quake struck at 9:21 AM local time (821 UTC).

The strongest earthquake to be recorded in the Aleutians since September 11 was a magnitude 5.8 quake that struck in 2002.

The Aleutians were devastated in the 1997/98 Asian tsunami when an 8.0 magnitude quake was recorded at 9:18 AM.

The Aleutians experienced a 6.9 magnitude quake near Surtsey on June 21, 2013 and two moderate quakes hit the area in 2000/01.

The Aleutian Islands were devastated in a magnitude 8.1 seismic event at 5:45 AM on January 12, 2015.

Syracuse, NY -- Two victims of a burglary that led to charges against Syracuse University football players are accused of burglarizing two other apartments minutes after being victimized, a county prosecutor said.

The two burglaries occurred about 5:40 a.m. May 23 and 2:45 p.m. on May 24 at a home on the 6400 block of North Highland Avenue in East Syracuse, prosecutor Joe Corbo said.

One of the victims told police officers when they entered the home they were confronted by an intruder, Corbo said. The suspect then pointed a handgun at the victim and stole $1,000 in cash from the victim's purse, he said.

The two victims, who are not Syracuse University football players, are facing burglary charges, Corbo said. The victims' identities have not been released.

Corbo said detectives believe the burglaries were part of a series of burglaries that began around noon on Tuesday, May 22 at three Syracuse University apartments in the 100 block of Main Street East in Syracuse.

Dropbox and Google Drive are very different services that appeal to different users. While Drive is connected to the entire Google Apps (now known as G Suite) ecosystem, Dropbox is just a cloud storage option that supports Google Drive-related features, such as sync over Wi-Fi or Dropbox Drive's ability to work with Google Docs. A recent Dropbox redesign has made this possible.

If you're already a Dropbox user and you want to transfer your documents to Drive in a few clicks, then you need to install a Google Drive plugin. These plugins, commonly referred to as "drive extensions," add a few options to the Dropbox UI. When you click on these options, you will be taken to Google's web platform, where Google Drive can be opened for viewing. If you're not already using one of Google's drive extensions, you're in the right place. With Drive extensions, you can view your documents in Google Drive, Google Drive-compatible PDF viewers, Google Drive-compatible Office applications (such as OneNote), Google Drive desktop client—and more.

Found it: Deputy looking for cow in road hits cow in road  A Kanabec County sheriff's deputy found a dead cow in the road after an 11-hour shift on Dec. 7, he said.

An investigation determined the cow had been hit by the deputy's patrol truck, the chief said, and the deputy sustained only scrapes and minor bruises.

The deputy was responding to a report "of possible human disturbance" and saw smoke in the air behind a truck, police said.

The deputy, who has been with the department for six years, didn't realize the cow was inside until he went into the truck and saw it, Chief Jeffrey A. Halloran said.

After the cow was found, the deputy spoke with the owner and she told him to bring it to the department's hospital as quickly as possible — even though she knew the cow was dead, Halloran said.

Instead, it turned out she played the part of an African-American prostitute named 'Miss Kanya' for a photo op with her Japanese fans when she wasn't really dressed in a traditional kimono. The actress has said before that the song was inspired by her own experiences of prostitution in the Philippines.

Data is the foundation of pay-per-click marketing; it's both the by-product of every action undertaken, and the source of denoting which action is the most effective.

Pay-per-click marketers need better and more complete data because their effectiveness is not limited by what they achieve on the other end. While they may be able to convince prospective buyers, they are largely dependent off of the sales volume achieved. It costs a lot of money to have buyers, and they are not going to keep your company afloat in business if you only have customers in the millions.

Now this data can be collected across many types of campaigns, but it is generally collected through the use of tracking headers – information which is then logged to allow search engines to determine what pages people are viewing, where they are looking to purchase, and the actions they are taking.

Then it was just her head.

It took me about four seconds to realize that she was not walking a straight line.

That she was twisting and jerking it. She kept leaning back when she looked over her shoulder. I'm not sure what this was, but I got up and started walking behind her.

"Do I have to? I'm a little confused." I tried to say. I was scared, and I didn't understand, and then I looked over at her, and she put her hands in front of her mouth to say "no." But that wasn't what it looked like.

I guess I could feel the heat up there. Her hands weren't there anymore.

A young woman who went to her bank to reset her PIN number was refused service after staff said her number was not included on the list of valid users.

The incident happened in Southwark, west London, on Wednesday night.

A 21-year-old student went to her local branch of Barclays in an attempt to reset her PIN number.

However, staff told her they could not help her, according to the woman.

She said: "My manager did tell me I could not use my PIN and so I went back to my local branch to get her card back.

"I went over to the ATM and when I got to the top to withdraw money, I noticed there was nothing on the ATM screen.

"The woman behind the counter asked me if I could see my card, but I was at the top and couldn't see it."

The woman went to her bank's helpline, and she was told the issue was a customer error, as her number was not part of the list of valid users.

Polls: Trump draws closer against Clinton in Wisconsin  Hillary Clinton's advantage over Donald Trump is slipping in a new Bloomberg/Des Moines Register/Bloomberg poll.

Hillary Clinton's edge over Donald Trump in a head-to-head match-up in Wisconsin is shrinking. A survey released Friday shows the Democratic nominee and Republican front-runner in a statistical tie in the state.

Among likely voters, Clinton had a 46 percent to 41 percent advantage over Trump, compared with a 43 percent to 38 percent lead in the Sept. 10-16 survey. Fifty-eight percent of independent voters said they were supporting Clinton, while 42 percent were backing Trump.

Story Continued Below

The race is closer than it was four years ago, when Trump was at 50 percent to 42 percent.

The poll in the state, the critical early primary contest for both candidates, puts Clinton in the comfortable territory required to win the Democratic nomination and advance to the general election, when the Republican nominee must win over primary voters in a more contested contest.

Feline Leukemia Virus Infection (FeLV) in Cats  Feline leukemia virus (FeLV) is a disease that impairs the cat's immune system and can cause leukemia. The disease is caused by the L1 retrotransposon in most forms. It is one of the leading causes of cat leukemia and an inherited disease that can progress rapidly even without treatment. FeLV is mainly seen in cats with either an abnormal Feline Leukemia Virus (FeLV) gene (mutation) or an abnormal Feline Leukemia Virus (FeLV) gene (synonymous mutation). There are two common forms of FeLV: the IgM and the IgG. These are the two virus proteins that are present on the cell surface of FeLV patients. The normal M1 gene for FIV is missing from each cat, but in the IgG and IgGV form of the virus the M1 gene is present; however, the IgG variant is known to be more infectious. A two-year-old San Diego law credited with preventing boats and large campers from monopolizing parking spots, especially near the Embarcadero waterfront.

The law, passed in 2011, mandates that all vehicles be parked in spaces allocated to parking spaces for carpoolers, walkers, bicycles and buses. The law's passage sparked complaints from motorists who feared to park in front of homes or businesses, and the parking space that was designated for carpoolers instead became reserved for RV's.

The law led to a massive parking crunch.

In one recent instance, a truck carrying 50 trucks, mostly trailers, ran out of space at Ocean Beach and had to park on the corner of California Street in Mission Bay until it was resolved, officials said.

The city of San Diego created a website to notify drivers of the requirement to use the appropriate spaces based on the distance between the curb and the vehicle, including parking in front of an apartment block, a restaurant or an athletic practice.

Germany's DB ICE train arrives at the Dusseldorf train station. The trains are capable of going up to 150 kilometres per hour. The trains are fitted with electronic devices, enabling automatic train control.

The main difference between ICE trains and normal train traffic is that when an ICE train is not passing through a station it does not cause an alarm. The ICE trains also allow the operators to use electronic aids or signal systems to assist with communication with trains that have been delayed.

How fast does an ICE train need to go?

The speed of an ICE train is a function of the level of traffic, the route that the ICE train is taking, and the location where the ICE train has stopped, with the speed of train being capped to a maximum of 75 kilometres per hour (44 mph).

About the Museum  The Icelandic Phallological Museum is probably the only museum in the world to contain a collection of phallic specimens belonging to all the world's phallic-bearing mammals. These fossils were discovered at the Phäleste Geological Museum in 2011 on the island of Snaefellsjökull, which was once part of North Iceland, and was the centre of volcanic activity. Phallodactyl fossils of a wide range of species have been found in the collection, which includes molar teeth, horns, horns of the deer family (including the molar of a horse), long horns, and teeth of all sorts, including many types of deer. There are three main groups of phallology specimens in the museum, including the phallus and its associated phallus, the phallus and the udders, and the molar teeth, all of which can be seen here. A new exhibit, 'The Human Origins of the Phalloid', is currently under construction, and it is due to open in 2019. It is a two-floor room, set high on the second floor.

By the 2030s, declining oxygen levels will likely be evident in many of the world's oceans. (NOAA via National Science Foundation)  What happens if marine life in the oceans can't adapt because of global warming? It's estimated that as much as 25 percent of the world's marine species may disappear by 2050 for lack of oxygen, the leading single cause of mortality in marine mammals such as whales and tuna. That's because a growing amount of plankton (small shells that break down into hydrogen) in the oceans is a major source of oxygen for marine life, the primary "fuel" for photosynthesis needed to produce food and oxygen for all life on Earth. The ocean is also home to more than 300 other species, such as blue whales and sea turtles. These organisms need a lot of oxygen to get through the day and are especially vulnerable under the impacts of climate change. But if oxygen levels fall too low, they could go extinct in a matter of years. (NOAA via National Science Foundation)

The latest in a string of successful court challenges to college "free speech zones" is unfolding in Virginia, where lawyers are arguing that the university's decision to prevent students from taking part in a campus gay pride rally violated students' free speech and associational rights.

Last month, the school announced it would deny a permit for the event to the Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund (LLDF), which seeks to protect LGBT people and minority groups and defends free speech on university campuses.

The university argued that Lambda is not a recognized student organization on campus and had not submitted a formal proposal to host the event, The Daily Caller reported.

It also said that the protest violated the university's policy barring protests, rallies, assemblies, or other demonstrations that interfere with the exercise of university rights.

The school argued that the protest organizers exceeded the limits of free speech because they included the message that the rally was sponsored by a private individual, which is prohibited by the campus student code of conduct. The university also argued that the protesters had not notified the university of their plans to attend the rally.

It was here that Mengele experimented on concentration camp inmates, using methods he had developed in the field of human guinea-pigs. There was not a single case of disease documented among them. The doctor had studied the disease pathology of humans, including those who had been experimented upon. In fact, the camp doctor had observed that among the inmates, diseases such as typhus were rare. He had seen them, however, at some time. They had all suffered from typhus as did the Nazis. Mengele, however, was a special case. He was an expert in genetic diseases and he was able to diagnose a disease in an inmate, no matter how ill he was. Census History: Counting Hispanics  Despite the long history of Hispanic residents in the United States, there was no systematic effort to count Hispanics, according to the census. In 1960, the census asked respondents whether they were of Hispanic origin, but did not list Hispanics by name. As a result, the total number of people who responded did not provide information on the actual number of Hispanics living in the United States. In 1963, Congress passed legislation to require that Hispanics be counted by the census. In 1970, the administration of President Richard Nixon issued an end-use census to include persons who identified as both Hispanics and non-Hispanic and to make sure any changes to the existing count were implemented. In this report, the number of estimates from this survey are presented. It is important to note that the end-use census provides fewer estimates of Hispanics, because it includes only persons who identified as Hispanic. The Census Bureau conducted a similar survey in 1989 covering a small sample of the Hispanic population. In this 1997 report, we present estimates of the number of Hispanics in Washington State who were 16 years of age or older in 1997.

Their leaders failed to keep Japan running smoothly. They let public debt balloon. They allowed the government to borrow money out of thin air. The officials said the bombers wore uniforms and blew themselves up as the congregants were leaving the church, a common strategy among Lebanese Islamist militants. In the 1950's, the American psychologist Solomon Asch recruited participants at Swarthmore College (United States) for a now famous experiment.* He told them he was doing research on perception and cognition, and he was interested in studying the effects of sleep on memory, and he was going to ask their help.

They volunteered to participate. He invited them to take a nap right after work or at the end of a long day of work (such as a 10 hour day), and he told them that the purpose of the nap was to test the relationship between sleep loss and memory.

He gave each participant a pill at 6am, and he recorded which person woke up. He divided the participants into two groups: the first, who were allowed to sleep through the pill and still had 20 minutes for the morning. The second group, who were not allowed to sleep through the pill and only had a 10 minute nap, was told they were "napping" and then they were told to take a nap.

Asch asked the participants to describe to him what they experienced while they were asleep--their subjective experience--and he recorded their responses. Asch looked

The University of Washington's Julie Carpenter is one of a handful of researchers worldwide investigating human emotional attachment to robots. Her work looks at the attachment of U.S. military bomb disposal personnel to their explosive-disposing robots.

"It's a very different attachment process," Carpenter said. "You have the person who looks like a robot."

Carpenter works with a robot called the M113, which is a robot called the M1. The robots take two to three months to reach full function, but the robots become extremely loyal to their handlers. They are extremely fast and accurate but also incredibly sensitive to even the slightest changes in their environment. They are trained to take over when the bomb disposal company is called away, and they will often do it regardless of whatever's happening on the ground.

"Most of them are on guard duty 24/7. There's a lot of emotion involved," Carpenter said. "They are incredibly good at protecting people and helping people."

But when the bomb team is in the field, this emotional attachment is often lost, and the robot's behavior will be different than it was before its training.

The first job of my rabbinic career was as a campus rabbi at University of Southern California for the Jewish Awareness Movement. One of my primary responsibilities was to lead large groups of Jewish college students into an atmosphere of unity. My task was to ensure they felt able to talk about every aspect of their relationship with Judaism in a manner that would enable them to discuss all of our shared values, including our differences. At this time I was working for the Board of Overseers of the Center for Jewish Life at the University of Minnesota, the flagship campus of the University of SouthernCalifornia, where we had just finished the first Jewish student organization at a large public university, in the fall of 1977. This organization, I was told later, was being founded as a Jewish campus organization: a campus group where Jews were encouraged to meet up in groups to talk about their Jewish identities, as well as to share their experiences in Jewish life with one another.

In our study period, at the end of my third semester as a student leader on the UCLA campus, we got involved in a controversy over how the Jewish community and students of all faiths should talk to one another.

Crohn's disease (CD) is a complex disorder resulting from the interaction of intestinal microbiota with the immune system. Several factors, including CD, can lead to a substantial prevalence of inflammatory bowel disease and, as a result, inflammation is considered a marker of disease burden. CD is associated with increased levels of the cytokines interleukin, interleukin-6, tumor necrosis factor-alpha, and interleukin-1 beta. Inflammation is believed to be triggered by a variety of stimuli, including inflammatory cells, food allergy, antibiotics, and medications (1).

Recently, numerous investigators, particularly those studying immune activation in CD, have argued that gut microbiota may play a role in the initiation and progression of the disorder (2–6). The prevalence of CD among individuals with autoimmune disease has been increasing in the last decade, which has led to increased recognition that alterations in microbiota may be at least partially responsible for the pathophysiology of the disease, perhaps more so than the presence of immune dysfunction (7). Originally Posted by simulatedworld Originally Posted by How do you know when the map will actually be visible?

You are wrong. When the terrain is fully lit by the player light, everything will be rendered. The map will not be rendered when it is partially lit.

The light from the player light is calculated in the background (when the area is fully opaque) so you will see "empty" areas in the rendered environment or in the rendered world when the lighting on the terrain is too low.

This problem is solved by making the render light source a fixed distance from the screen (for example by having the player light be 100 pixels away from the screen or by having the player light only 100 pixels from the player).

Treasurer Joe Hockey says Commonwealth debt limit being increased to $500 billion, up from $300-billion.

The Treasurer says his government is taking urgent action to increase Australia's fiscal position.

Mr Hockey said the $500 billion increase was necessary to avoid the annual cost of servicing the debt to peak at more $100 billion by 2014.

"That is still below our target of $300 billion this year. This is an important target at a critical time in our country's economic development. It is also one that was endorsed by the G20 summit just a few weeks ago," he said in a statement.

"The G20 is now reviewing its fiscal policy to ensure it works in Australia's best interests."

The CDC states that the condition is not caused by an infection or anything in the environment.  The CDC study also included a lab analysis of skin fibers in Morgellons patients. The fibers in the study suggested that Morgellons causes allergic reactions in an unusual way.  In these people's lungs and skin, the pollen-like proteins from the Morgellon pollen could cause a condition called acute bronchitis.  This is a very rare type of asthma. Allergic reactions often occur within the first few days of exposure, and in this case, the reaction occurred within three days after exposure.  In a 2009 study, researchers found that the skin of Morgellon patients had fibers more commonly found on rats compared to humans.  In their studies, researchers found that the skin fibers in the study were more likely to come from the lungs of the Morgellons patients.

Some Morgellons patients say they smell the insects on their shoes or from their pets. While not sure of the role these odors play, scientists in this area have found that Morgellons may cause more complex allergic conditions such as hay fever.

I used Cisco Packet Tracer 5.1, which is a simulation piece of software that emulates the routers, supplied by work. On the diagrams it's shown as a "sport", in which the IP address of the client is displayed. On the right page you can see that the IP is being sent to the "client".

Since the router is running a DHCP server, a client with the ip address configured as 192.168.0* will receive a valid IP address from that router.

You can try to configure your network device with 192.168.* as the IP address and 192.0.0* as the gateway, but it only works on the client computers. If you want to test the connection using an unpatched operating system, you'll have to try it yourself.

Another way of configuring your local IP address is through a router configuration protocol like WANIP, which is available and documented in this excellent post.

Why are so few disabled people employed, compared with non-disabled people? How should governments and employers close the so-called "disabled employment gap"? Who should benefit from more disabled talent?

A large body of evidence shows that disabled workers, rather than being a "lump of labour" as some argue, are valuable and highly-skilled workers, capable of doing the work required.

The UK is now the most expensive place to hire a disabled employee, with only 5pc of disabled people receiving disability-related pay. More than twice as many UK disabled workers were sacked between April 2009 (27,000) and April 2010 (46,000) and the number of companies found to have violated employment law during this period rose from one to 10.

If one in five disabled people was not working, the amount lost to the economy would be around £1 billion a year. Yet only 0.7pc of disabled workers were employed in 2009, and it turns out that the average salary of a UK disabled worker is only £23,000 a year.

Ph.D. Program  The Doctoral Program in Women and Gender Studies (DWGS) offers a variety of interdisciplinary interdisciplinary Master's degrees offered primarily under the direction of a faculty member. Students will develop the theoretical foundations of their disciplines by working in a team or with faculty members. The program consists of a six-year program of courses designed to equip students to think, teach, and write about women and gender as a class, as individual, or as societal category. Students are trained through the application of multiple approaches to critical analysis of the social, historical, economic, legal, and political contexts of the studies of women and gender, as identified within the social sciences. Programs in the Faculty of Arts and Sciences offer both professional and graduate degrees. The Professional Doctoral degree is the highest degree that a doctorate in gender studies can attain. This degree program allows the Doctor of Arts and Sciences to establish an academic and professional record by completing the Master's degree requirements to the degree. In late-18th-century America, something of minimal value was often described as being "not worth a continental." In the United States, on the other hand, that value of "not worth a Continental," in its simplest sense, would be something like a hundredth of that of "not worth a dollar." A hundredth of a dollar in 1775 would be worth less than anything of value before 1775.

And these "dollar values" were not the only ways in which America was different than England. Some people thought of America as a land of the free, the home of the brave—except for the British soldiers who patrolled its shores and, as they often did, killed and enslaved Native American women and children. Another way in which America could be different—and thus superior to England—was that it was a place where the average Englishman felt he could own land, but Englanders could not, until 1688, own land. "England has an interest in that," Alexander Hamilton told his friends. "It has a right of owning land in America."

To stop a rooster from crowing, make a collar out of double-sided tape. Start just above the point of the feather and wrap the tape around the tail. Then start wrapping the tape around the back legs of the rooster. The double-sided tape will form a circle with the tail. It should reach the point where the rooster does not move, and the inside of the circle should just be the rooster's legs. The next step is to take the tape, put it around the inside of the front legs of the rooster (this takes more time and is harder to do, but it helps) and tie a knot (the ends of the tape can be attached with scissors, just don't cut the tape). Finally, put the chicken outside the cage and have an assistant hold the chicken inside with all the tapes so the chicken does not have to come out on his own. Once again, do not let the chicken come out on his own.

Why RSC can happen in the first place and How to handle it

As you probably know, Windows has a couple of security methods (security classes) that can be used to help prevent security risks. RSC (Receive Segment Coalescing) is one such method. As RSC allows windows to combine the packet data in some way without going through the Windows Secure Socket Layer (SSL) network stack, security experts would advise against using Windows 7 for the purpose. In this case, the Windows security methods wouldn't help you because RSC only works for the local network. They won't help if you're using a remote machine on the internet. And because these services aren't managed by Microsoft, there's only so much of a threat posed by it.

It is therefore possible to study the relations between the productive and circulation factors, or between money and the value of the stuff it is used for.

As a matter of fact, if we want to understand the difference between the two, we need to have the history of money from its beginnings and in the process of development of its forms. If we do this, there is no doubt that we will be able to see a very important distinction between the production and circulation phase of capitalism.

In the beginning, every single commodity that was produced had a value of its own. This value did not consist of a fixed quantity of commodities, but rather of the labour necessary to produce them. Taking full advantage of the law of supply and demand, people who choose to take a less-expensive route tend to sell their property and/or trade up to the next-cheapest home or unit in the area. Since prices are determined by supply and demand and this is a highly elastic process, the amount of vacant, high-cost property is relatively unchanged over time despite the large number of people living in the area and their relative price increase.

The graph shows how prices increase with increased vacancy rate over successive months. The blue line is for the January-September period. Prices rise as houses are taken off the market due to increasing vacancy rate. However while prices may temporarily lag the rental market when houses are being snapped up by the short-sale market, over time house prices are fully absorbed by the market, leaving renters with relatively little space to rent.

Millions of native oysters are to be put into the Solent, once the site of Europe's largest oyster fishery.  The five-year project aims first to harvest 2.1m tons of oysters, and then to release them to the wild, where they can then develop.

In the past, most of the oyster beds have been fenced off because of the impact they have on the coastal environment. "The impact of the fishery is much more profound because it is on the seafloor, it's under water," says James Grieve, who heads the oyster management effort for the Marine Conservation Society. The plan is now to remove more than 2,000 square kilometers of oyster beds to free the coastal ecosystems.

Grieve stresses that the project is purely about saving the natural habitat of the oyster, and there will not be any major changes to the estuaries where the oysters occur. One reason is that oysters can swim much deeper than other crustaceans, which have to spend long periods in saltwater.

The government deficit: The total amount a government spends minus revenues from federal taxes that are not included in the deficit is called the gross federal debt. The government's gross debt includes debt held by agencies in other categories, such as the Federal Reserve.

The deficit also represents a government's liabilities, such as interest payments it owes to its creditors, such as bondholders, and the amount of money the government currently owes its people. The deficit includes what the government spends minus what it collects from its taxes. So to be balanced by 2013, the government would have to reduce the gross debt. By 2014, the government would have to have reduced the deficit more severely. By 2017, the government would no longer need to reduce the deficit.

BIOS Password Backdoors in Laptops Synopsis: The mechanics of BIOS password locks present in current generation laptops are briefly outlined. Trivial mechanisms have been employed, with a strong password (usually on the system disk) acting as the master key. The laptop password keys can change, allowing the owner to change what password is used. If the password is compromised, the laptop becomes essentially the bootloader of choice. The user must then enter a unique login key with every boot. This key is then inserted at the start of each bootup, typically through a password prompt. We will describe how this works. Laptops are not the only target for BIOS password locks. In addition, the Laptops with the most advanced security features become the most interesting to lock to a specific password.

Summary: A well known password, commonly used by most users, is not secure anymore in modern BIOS systems; however, the weak password can be exploited to achieve root access.

What does Zero Times Infinity Equal?  At first, you may think that zero times infinity equals zero. After all, zero times any number has the same meaning that it would have if we didn't have the "zero" in it, which makes zero times any number equal zero, doesn't it? For any number, there must either be a zero, or it can't be anything. For instance, you would think that there could only be two numbers whose sum would equal the sum of a pair of equal-by-value integers; if there were no such pairs, the value of the two integers would be the sum of their sums multiplied by 1. But this can't be. The "zero" in "zero times infinity" is a meaningless, meaningless number. We can't say that two are equal-by-value ints by dividing the values of the integers, even if that doesn't matter. The emergency contraceptive pill (morning after pill) is an artificial hormonal form of the female hormone progestin that is taken from a pill or implant. Each year, millions of Americans take emergency contraception pills; the number has actually increased over the years, because the pill is less risky than pregnancy (though it will not prevent pregnancy if sex is attempted during an emergency contraception pill). Emergency contraception is intended to prevent pregnancy if you are unable to have sex that day, or if the sex is interrupted, at a vulnerable time, or when the hormones are insufficient in dose.

Like other reversible birth control methods, the morning after pill has serious, long-term side effects, including:

Abortion

Hormonal birth control pills do reduce the risk of developing the very rarer "miscarriage" — an unexpected pregnancy. But only if you are prepared with a backup plan, at least 24 hours before you would like to have sex. It may be more difficult to prevent abortion in those cases.

"It also provides better transportation for all Torontonians, including the millions who ride for free every day on our free public transit network."

Uber's business model of relying on a large fleet of drivers instead of a network of traditional taxi lines, has worked surprisingly well in Toronto, where only 3 per cent of Canadians say they usually rely on a private taxi. MANILA, Philippines — President Rodrigo Duterte has signed a new law prohibiting the government's purchase of private land.

In the latest development in Duterte's "war" on illegal drugs, The Bulacan Governor's Office said the proposed law, which will soon be presented to the Cabinet, prohibits the government from buying land from the public without going through the Public Land Office, the government's administrative body.

The law bans the public purchase of land because it is "in violation of law" and is in contravention of the provisions against acquisition of land by the public without proper permits.

Acne, commonly referred to as pimples, is the most common skin disease treated by physicians. It is a chronic condition that affects more than half of all adolescents and young adults age 13 and older in the United States. In 2012, the average age of first-time acne patients was 14.7 years old, with 2.7% of all adolescents and young adults having acne.[1]

As many as 30% of adults have some form of acne. During adolescence, acne is more commonly found in adolescent girls.

Acne can be treated in adolescents, or it is more likely to occur when the body is under stress or under the influence of drugs, alcohol, nicotine, sedatives, or drugs of abuse. peculium castrense: a soldier whose father was still lving could dispose of everything he acquired in military service, i.e. with the permission of his father, at his own discretion, without even making any attempt to redeem the spoils. This rule was not applied to other men (excepting, of course, the slaves), and the soldiers of the Roman Empire acquired an enormous quantity of superfluous wealth, and an immense share of public expenses. The soldiers of a feudal state, under the authority of their lord or of their king, were compelled, however with difficulty, to sell at their own discretion, the property which they were entrusted with, and to give it to the feudal lord, or to their king when the latter came to the throne. However, the feudal lord could always at any moment, by writing to the governor or by a just process of justice, claim what he ought to have received from the soldiers for the service done by them.

The latter is more convenient and more accurate, but it requires you to manually select the CPU activity and the amount of time being tracked.

In my tests, I ran a Windows 10 CPU utilization test once a week for an entire month. The results were then graphed using CNet's CPU utilization data visualizer, which allows users to plot the percentage and time it takes to perform computations.

In a new article in Nature Climate Change scientists from NOAA's Cooperative Institute for Marine and Atmospheric Studies show maps that illustrate how rising sea temperatures are likely to affect all coral reefs and some fish populations from tropical areas around the world into the future.

"One implication for this is that we should be investing in strategies to mitigate the impacts of future sea level rise. As we get deeper into the century, we will see even more extensive areas of our ocean becoming unsuitable for living, including reefs as well as areas of ocean with lots of fish, including some that are critically important for human populations."

Ocean warming 'has already caused catastrophic changes'

Coral reefs, or cays, cover more than 50% of the world's ocean floor.

The Massachusetts Department of Education has issued a new guidance document to schools, the first from a state agency since the landmark guidance issued by the Obama HHS last summer. The guidance documents are meant to help schools communicate with transgender students — who can use the bathrooms and locker rooms of the gender with which they identify — about how to help support their privacy. The language was developed in conjunction with three federal agencies, including the Department of Education and the Department of Justice.

Transgender student advocates are delighted, saying it will provide more clarity on how to help transgender students in Massachusetts.

"This new policy is clear in providing guidance for schools to ensure compliance with the law, and ensures all students are treated equally and protected from discrimination in all forms," said Sarah Gillian, executive director of the Massachusetts Transgender Justice Alliance. "Our community is one of the most heavily stigmatized in the United States and schools must play a leadership role by helping to foster a climate where transgender students feel safe to explore their gender identity."

Sure, Philips' color-changing Hue light bulbs can give you calendar or weather reminders, but if you buy them for practical reasons, you're doing it wrong.

The technology behind the bulbs is simple, but still allows for some pretty complex behavior. Philips' bulbs have a built-in, LED display that lights up any color you throw at it—not just green or blue. For instance, you could set the LEDs to show you the weather during high-profile events, including the Super Bowl—but you're almost certainly not going to see this because the LEDs are not actually used for that purpose. You're just hoping for a sunny day, the kind of day you'd want a calendar reminder for.

In most cases, there's no need to know what hue each bulb is using—your clock is likely to do the same thing anyway.

OBJECTIVES:  The popular herbal remedy St John's wort is an inducer of hyperglycemia. Its activity against non-oxidative pathways of glycation has not been adequately investigated. The results of this study are therefore to determine the ability of St. John's wort to inhibit lipid peroxidation in the absence of a free radical.

METHODS:  We investigated the ability of St. John's wort, a plant commonly used as an herbal tea, to inhibit lipid peroxidation in human subjects. We used lipid peroxidation reaction monitoring and electron cryomicroscopy to analyze the lipid peroxidation status of human serum and skin collagen and the extent of lipid oxidation.

RESULTS:  St. John's wort showed significant inhibitory effects on non-oxidative lipid peroxidation in serum, collagen, and skin. Omar Abdelkader, a student at Northeastern University in Boston, is an outspoken critic of the Muslim Brotherhood whom the American-based Muslim Reform Movement in 2008 designated a "terrorist." The movement's leaders, known in the West as the Mujahideen-e-Khalq, have declared allegiance to al-Qaeda.

"What do they really want and what's in it for them?" Abdulkader told Al Jazeera America. "Islam demands respect and the rights of women. What they're saying is we're not going to pay any ransom to them for protection - and that's really what they're saying."

The Obama administration has taken other precautions beyond military surveillance of the Brotherhood. It recently placed a $10 million bounty on the group's leader and has taken measures to protect Muslim women from violence.

In April, the Justice Department began investigating a New York City chapter of the Brotherhood for its alleged ties to a 2010 bombing that killed four people and wounded nearly two dozen others on the eve of New York City's Democratic National Convention .

GLENSHAW (KDKA) — Nine people, including seven children, have been injured after officials say some ductwork fell from the roof of a building during a thunderstorm last night.

City officials and fire officials say the storm brought a downpour of rain that damaged electrical and water fixtures, causing ductwork to fail on buildings located along the South Side, including The Vineyard.

Crews responded at 5:38 PM, and after they removed the affected items from the building, they determined eight people were trapped inside and had to be removed.

Officials said the deceased were one male and four females. Six of the survivors — all with critical injuries — were taken to the hospital.

At this point, no other victims are known.

Officials say their investigation will likely take several hours because of the weather.

Officials said no one was in the area when the storm hit.
